Lamb’s Conduit Street’s claim to being one of London’s most intriguing shopping destinations. The shop is quite literally dark (the walls and lampshades black), creating a blank canvas for the carefully chosen selection of unisex fashion, accessories and interiors items on sale. Designer items include Borba Margo bags, DMK glassware and Solomia ceramics. The space doubles up as a gallery, with displays (such as etchings by artist Marcus James) intermingling with a range of sculptural jewellery by Florian, Scott Wilson and Maria Francesca Pepe. Each piece begs the question – do I wear it or hang it on the wall?";s:10:"post_title";s:8:"Darkroom";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:8:"darkroom";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2015-05-06 13:11:03";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2015-10-23 11:51:12";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";i:0;s:4:"guid";s:76:"https://pixelgrade.com/demos/listable-stock/?post_type=job_listing&amp;p=691";s:10:"menu_order";i:0;s:9:"post_type";s:11:"job_listing";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";s:6:"filter";s:3:"raw";}i:32;O:7:"WP_Post":24:{s:2:"ID";i:629;s:11:"post_author";s:1:"1";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2015-05-04 17:26:27";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2015-10-23 09:41:53";s:12:"post_content";s:629:"Step inside the Museum of London for an unforgettable journey through the capital''s turbulent past. Discover prehistoric London, see how the city changed under Romans and Saxons, wonder at medieval London and examine the tumultuous years when London was ravaged by civil wars, plague and fire.\n\nThen venture into the Galleries of Modern London where you can walk the streets of Victorian London, take a stroll in recreated pleasure gardens and marvel at the magnificent Lord Mayor''s Coach.\n\nFrom 9 October 2015, never-before-seen-objects from the Metropolitan Police’s Crime Museum will go on display in a major new exhibition.";s:10:"post_title";s:16:"Museum of London";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:16:"museum-of-london";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2015-05-04 17:26:27";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2015-10-23 09:41:53";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";i:0;s:4:"guid";s:76:"https://pixelgrade.com/demos/listable-stock/?post_type=job_listing&amp;p=629";s:10:"menu_order";i:0;s:9:"post_type";s:11:"job_listing";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";s:6:"filter";s:3:"raw";}i:33;O:7:"WP_Post":24:{s:2:"ID";i:784;s:11:"post_author";s:1:"1";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2015-04-26 15:52:15";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2015-10-23 13:15:47";s:12:"post_content";s:488:"New and vintage design meet in this design store beloved of, and frequented by, Islington’s substantial coterie of architects, designers and other assorted trendies. Quality, beautifully-designed homeware is carefully sourced and advice on investing in classic retro furniture (or splashing out on a contemporary piece) is always on hand. If money is tight, hold out for one of Twentytwentyone''s many sample sales, often offering up to 75 per cent off ex-display and discontinued items.";s:10:"post_title";s:15:"Twentytwentyone";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:15:"twentytwentyone";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2015-04-26 15:52:15";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2015-10-23 13:15:47";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";i:0;s:4:"guid";s:76:"https://pixelgrade.com/demos/listable-stock/?post_type=job_listing&amp;p=784";s:10:"menu_order";i:0;s:9:"post_type";s:11: